In the hope of being useful for some others, here is how I solved the problem, reducing the queries from 2k to a handful in the admin:

    class MyModelAdminForm(TranslatableModelForm):
        class Meta:
            model = MyModel
            exclude = ()
    
        def __init__(self, *args, **kwargs):
            super(MyModelAdminForm, self).__init__(*args, **kwargs)
            self.fields['services'].queryset = Service.objects.prefetch_related('translations').all()
    
    class MyModelAdmin(TranslatableAdmin):
    
        form = MyModelAdminForm

So, override the form, and once inside, override the queryset with prefetch.

@dannyroberts thanks for making these updates.  Now that I see the tests I think I'm understanding better how it works.  I'd like to play with it some before I merge the pull request, but I think it looks reasonable, as long as we document the limitations clearly.  I hadn't quite registered that the specified order only affected content set at initialization time - although of course it is right there in your pull request title.

I've been thinking about the ordering and wondering if it wouldn't be useful to have some kind of ordering logic like this available in the XmlObject directly (optional, of course) and not just in a custom subclass.  However, in order to incorporate it there, we'd need to figure out a way to also allow constraining nodes that are added after the object has already been initialized, but I'm not sure yet how to make the ordering logic available in the field descriptors that actually create new xml elements.  It might also be nice to make the ordering logic more extensible, although I'm not sure yet what other scenarios we might see.

If you have any additional thoughts on this please let me know.

@ThomasWalter I'm going from memory/intuition here rather than a full overview of the code, but if I remember correctly, the morphological reconstruction will run a dilation on the full image multiple times, enough to cover any plateaus. On the other hand, this algorithm only needs one pass over the image + some flood filling, so it can potentially be much faster.

Regarding the borders, we can reduce borderless to border-ful by padding with the minimum value. (Though this may not be the fastest/most efficient approach).

@lagru 

> for a connectivity of 2 in the 2D-case 8 offsets for each pixel (except for the edges) are required. So I would need memory at least 8 times the size of the provided image.

No, you compute the offsets "just in time", when you are observing each pixel/voxel. So you compute an offset array (a 4-, 8-, 6-, 18-, or 26-element array of signed ints) and when you check a pixel you compute its neighbors by adding the pixel coordinate to that array. You do *not* broadcast all pixel coordinates against the offset array! That would be [crazy](https://github.com/jni/gala/blob/24290bc8e954ff38c9a2c1e1d3896367a9791c40/gala/morpho.py#L643). =P (In my defense, I wrote this code a very long time ago. =D)

@oxtopus : I'll work through this. The problem is that pip and setuptools installed by travis are too old. Travis sets up its python packages in a strange way that makes it difficult to upgrade pip and setuptools, because sys.path lists their eggs explicitly at absolute paths. Even though the upgrade claims that it succeeded, the ones that get used are the old ones!

I think I need to use virtualenv myself to get the environment and package versions that I need to make the build work. This works fine with newer pip/setuptools.

I am also struggling to find meaningful documentation on travis's .travis.yml syntax. They are either  making it difficult to find or it just doesn't exist.

Thank you @mrcslws ! Now I understand your motivation, although I still don't think the logic is correct. 
Some notes: 

- I don't like the `do { ...} while (sample > smax)` for it adds non-determinism (in terms of RT-execution, not random values). 
  - so I removed the loop and all tests still work https://github.com/htm-community/nupic.cpp/pull/41/files#diff-737a75596163e5aa8085fd74441d2bd9L190
    - did the debug and currently the loop is always called exactly once!
      - Because: the undocumented function `RandomImpl->getUInt32(void)` https://github.com/htm-community/nupic.cpp/pull/41/files#diff-737a75596163e5aa8085fd74441d2bd9L227 does not do what one'd expect (uniform random numbers 0..UInt32:max), the samples just a HALF https://github.com/htm-community/nupic.cpp/pull/41/files#diff-737a75596163e5aa8085fd74441d2bd9L236
        - therefore the loop runs exactly once all the time.
 - could we use a standard uniform random distribution sampler from c++ instead? What is specific about its (`impl_->getUInt32(void)`) cryptic code? 
 - there should be a test for the phenomenon you describe "random biased towards zero"
   I did one:
  ```
/* when getUInt32() called without arg,
 * the RNG is slightly biased towards zero (0) (2x likely than
 * any other value). This is most visible with the empty
 * (UInt32::MAX) arg, less with any other (1024, etc),
 * Unlikely to run in CI, as current 3bil runs take ~6mins
 */
TEST(RandomTest, testGetUIntBiasToZero) {
  Random r1(421);
  UInt32 rnd;
  const UInt64 RUNS = 3* 10000000000;  //30 bil calls
  UInt32 zeroCount = 1; //both counts set to 1 to avoid division-by-zero
  UInt32 otherCount = 1; //say other =1

  for(UInt64 i=0; i< RUNS; i++) {
    rnd = r1.getUInt32();
    if(rnd==0) zeroCount++;
    else if(rnd==1) otherCount++;
  }
  NTA_WARN << "Random's bias towards zero: "
          << "zeros:" << zeroCount-1 << " ones: " << otherCount-1;
  ASSERT_NEAR(zeroCount/(Real)otherCount, 1.0f, 0.01f);
}
  ```
- even though, is it worth it? 
  > For example, with seed 19, it returns 0 on the 1009865459th call.

  so zero is 2* 1/billion more likely?

